          "body": "Verse 1 provides the psalm's entire foundation in two phrases: 'who fears the LORD' (*yare*) and 'who greatly delights in His commandments' (*meod chaphets*). These are not sequential stages or different types of believers — they are inseparable facets of a single orientation. Fear of the LORD without delight produces mere compliance; delight in the commandments without fear produces sentimentalism untethered from awe. The wisdom tradition consistently holds them together: 'The fear of the LORD is the beginning of wisdom' (Psalm 111:10; Proverbs 9:10), and 'I delight to do Your will, O my God; Your Law is within my heart' (Psalm 40:8). The psalm's beatitude (*esher*, 'O the blessedness of…') is the wisdom literature's formal declaration of a flourishing life — the same formula opening Psalm 1 and the Beatitudes of Matthew 5:3–11. By opening with this formula, the psalmist signals: what follows is not a to-do list but a portrait of someone who has found the grain of the universe and is living with it rather than against it."
