          "body": "Verses 2–9 are not a random sequence of blessings — they trace the God-fearer's righteousness across every sphere of human life. The domestic sphere comes first (vv.2–3): his household is marked by mighty descendants and enduring wealth, but the wealth is immediately reframed by the word 'righteousness' — it endures because it is rightly held and rightly used, not because it is large. The inner character follows (v.4): light in darkness for the upright who is gracious, compassionate, and righteous — three divine attributes worn by a human person. Then the social and economic sphere (vv.5–6): generous lending, affairs guided by justice, a character too rooted to be shaken, a name that will never be erased. The psychological interior is then pressed (vv.7–8): the heart that trusts the LORD is the heart that does not fear evil tidings. And the climactic virtue (v.9): he scatters abroad to the poor — the same verb (*pazar*, to scatter) used of free and joyful generosity. Calvin rightly observed that the God-fearer's generosity is not calculated but spontaneous, like seed scattered from an open hand rather than doled out by a counting hand. The portrait is not a biography of any one man; it is a composite icon of a life fully alive to God."
