        "number": 2,
        "title": "A portrait in eight verses — righteousness from household to horn",
        "range": "112:2-9",
        "excerpt": "Wealth and riches are in his house, and his righteousness endures forever.",
        "body": "Verses 2–9 are the psalm's central movement — an eight-verse portrait of the God-fearer's life across every sphere of human existence. The portrait is organized concentrically: from the household (vv.2–3) outward to character (v.4), to civic virtue (vv.5–6), to inner life under pressure (vv.7–8), and finally to the social act that climaxes the portrait (v.9). Reading the portrait this way reveals that the psalmist is not cataloguing random blessings but tracing the centrifugal radiation of a God-fearing character.\n\nThe household promises of vv.2–3 are deliberately framed. 'Wealth and riches are in his house' (v.3a) could be read as crude prosperity theology — until the second half of the verse asserts that 'his righteousness endures forever' (v.3b). The Hebrew syntax places these two clauses in immediate juxtaposition without a causal or adversative connector, forcing the reader to hear them as a single statement: the house has wealth, and the enduring reality of that house is its righteousness, not its riches. The same refrain returns at v.9 in the context of giving to the poor — what endures is not the wealth distributed but the righteousness expressed in the distribution. Peter Davids (*The First Epistle of Peter*, NIGTC) notes a comparable dynamic in 1 Peter 1:7, where what is 'tested by fire' and 'found genuine' is faith, not wealth, and faith is what endures.\n\nThe secondary beatitude at v.5 ('it is well with the man who is gracious and lends') is significant because it specifies the mechanism by which character becomes conduct. The God-fearer is not merely *described* as gracious (v.4) — he *acts* graciously by lending (v.5a) and conducting his affairs with justice (v.5b). Douglas Moo (*The Letter of James*, Pillar NTC) notes this same movement in James 2:14-26: faith that does not produce works of generosity is not genuine faith. Psalm 112 anticipates the same point in poetic form. Gracious character and just conduct are not two different virtues that happen to coincide; the one is the outworking of the other.\n\nThe refrain 'his righteousness endures forever' (vv.3, 9) is the psalm's structural and theological spine. Both occurrences use the same Hebrew construction (*tsedaqato omedeth la-ad*), and both are placed at climactic moments — the first summarizing the domestic portrait, the second summarizing the social portrait. The repetition is not accidental: the psalmist is insisting that the righteousness in view is not behavioral performance that can erode but a moral reality as durable as the covenant of God Himself. Psalm 111:3 uses identical language of the LORD's own righteousness — 'His righteousness endures forever.' The God-fearer's enduring righteousness is the human reflection of the divine original.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Tsedaqah* (righteousness) — covenant conformity expressed in both character and social action; broader than legal rectitude. *Amad* (endures) — to stand, to remain firm; a word used of mountains and covenants. *La-ad* (forever) — into the distant, unlimited future. The sequence *tsedaqah... amad... la-ad* is the psalm's strongest claim about the permanence of the God-fearer's moral legacy."
